Big O notation
🔢 Big O Notation (Quick Summary)
Big O notation describes how fast an algorithm grows as the input size (n) increases.

👉 It focuses on worst-case performance
👉 It ignores constants and small differences
👉 It tells you scalability, not exact time


🧠 Why it matters
When you're coding (especially for interviews or real systems), Big O helps you answer:
Will this work for 1,000 inputs?
What about 1 million?
Is this efficient enough?

📈 Common Time Complexities
Complexity    	Name	        Growth Rate	                Example
O(1)	        Constant	    No growth	                Access array index
O(log n)	    Logarithmic	    Very slow growth	        Binary search
O(n)	        Linear	        Grows with n	            Loop through array
O(n log n)	    Linearithmic	Slightly worse than linear	Merge sort
O(n²)	        Quadratic	    Gets slow fast	            Nested loops
O(2ⁿ)	        Exponential	    Extremely slow	            Recursive brute force
O(n!)	        Factorial	    Worst possible	            Permutations


⚡ Intuition (Super Important)

O(1) → Always fast,

O(log n) → Scales insanely well

O(n) → Acceptable

O(n²) → Dangerous for large inputs

O(2ⁿ) → Avoid unless n is tiny



🧩 Examples
1. Constant Time, when input size increases, time stays almost the same
arr[0]
👉 O(1)

2. Linear Time,input increases,time also increases
for i in arr:
    print(i)
👉 O(n)

3. Quadratic Time
for i in arr:
    for j in arr:
        print(i, j)
👉 O(n²)

4. Logarithmic Time
# Binary search
👉 O(log n)



🧮 Rules to Remember
1. Drop constants
O(2n) → O(n)

2. Drop lower-order terms
O(n² + n) → O(n²)

3. Nested loops multiply
O(n) * O(n) = O(n²)

4. Separate loops add
for i in arr:   # O(n)
for j in arr:   # O(n)
👉 O(n + n) = O(n)

🎯 Final Takeaway
👉 Big O = How your code scales when input grows
👉 Lower Big O = better performance
👉 In interviews, aim for O(n) or better




🧠 Space Complexity (Bonus)
Big O also measures memory usage:
O(1) → no extra memory
O(n) → extra array/list
O(n²) → matrix

🧠 What is Space Complexity?
👉 Space Complexity = How much extra memory your algorithm uses as input grows
It includes:
Variables
Data structures (arrays, lists, dicts)
Function call stack (recursion)

⚠️ Important Clarification
👉 We usually DON’T count input size itself
👉 We count extra/auxiliary space

📦 Types of Space Complexity
Type	    Meaning
O(1)	    Constant space (no extra memory grows)
O(n)	    Linear space (memory grows with input)
O(n²)	    Matrix/grid-like memory
O(log n)	Recursive stack (binary split)

🔍 Example 1: Constant Space — O(1)
def sum_array(arr):
    total = 0
    for num in arr:
        total += num
    return total
🧮 Calculation:
total → 1 variable
num → 1 variable
👉 Memory does NOT grow with n
✅ Space Complexity = O(1)

🔍 Example 2: Linear Space — O(n)
def copy_array(arr):
    new_arr = []
    for num in arr:
        new_arr.append(num)
    return new_arr
🧮 Calculation:
new_arr stores n elements
👉 If input = 5 → stores 5
👉 If input = 1000 → stores 1000
✅ Space Complexity = O(n)

🔍 Example 3: Two Arrays — Still O(n)
def double_copy(arr):
    arr1 = arr.copy()
    arr2 = arr.copy()
    return arr1, arr2
🧮 Calculation:
arr1 → n
arr2 → n
👉 Total = n + n = 2n
👉 Drop constant
✅ O(2n) → O(n)

🔍 Example 4: Nested Storage — O(n²)
def create_matrix(n):
    matrix = []
    for i in range(n):
        row = []
        for j in range(n):
            row.append(0)
        matrix.append(row)
    return matrix
🧮 Calculation:
n rows
each row has n elements
👉 Total = n × n = n²
✅ Space Complexity = O(n²)

🔍 Example 5: Recursion — O(n)
def factorial(n):
    if n == 0:
        return 1
    return n * factorial(n-1)
🧮 Calculation:
Each function call waits in memory
Stack depth = n
👉 If n = 5 → 5 calls in memory
✅ Space Complexity = O(n)

🔍 Example 6: Binary Recursion — O(log n)
def binary_search(arr, left, right, target):
    if left > right:
        return -1
    
    mid = (left + right) // 2
    
    if arr[mid] == target:
        return mid
    elif arr[mid] > target:
        return binary_search(arr, left, mid - 1, target)
    else:
        return binary_search(arr, mid + 1, right, target)
🧮 Calculation:
Each step halves the problem
Stack depth = log n
👉 Very efficient memory usage
✅ Space Complexity = O(log n)


⚡ Golden Rules (Super Important)
1. Variables = O(1)
Even if loop runs 1 million times → still constant space

2. New data structures = O(n)
If you create something that grows → count it

3. Recursion = stack space
Linear recursion → O(n)
Divide & conquer → O(log n)

4. Ignore constants
O(2n) → O(n)
O(n + 100) → O(n)

🧠 Intuition Trick (This is KEY)
Ask yourself:
👉 “Am I storing more stuff as input grows?”
❌ No → O(1)
✅ Yes, linearly → O(n)
✅ Yes, in grid → O(n²)

🎯 Final Understanding
Time Complexity = how long it takes
Space Complexity = how much memory it takes
👉 In interviews, optimized code = low time + low space




recognition patterns
🔹 1. Linear Scan → O(n)
for i in range(n):
    ...
🧠 Instinct:
“Touches every element once → O(n)”

🔹 2. Nested Loops → O(n²)
for i in range(n):
    for j in range(n):
        ...
🧠 Instinct:
“For each element, I scan all elements → O(n²)”

🔹 3. Shrinking / Halving → O(log n)
while n > 1:
    n //= 2
🧠 Instinct:
“Cuts problem in half → log n”

🔹 4. Loop + Log → O(n log n)
for i in range(n):
    binary_search(...)
🧠 Instinct:
“Do log n work for each element → n log n”

🔹 5. Branching Recursion → O(2ⁿ)
f(n-1) + f(n-2)
🧠 Instinct:
“Splitting into multiple paths → exponential”



👉 Rule: Number of nested loops = power of n
Nested Loops	Complexity
1 loop	O(n)
2 loops	O(n²)
3 loops	O(n³)